By Roman law, the goods are at the risk of the purchaser as soon as the contract is complete, and before the propertyis trans· ferred. The formula, res perit domino, therefore, does not apply to the contract of purchase and sale, as it does to other contracta, e. g. to mutuum, commodatum, pignus.

In English law, the risk always belongs to the person in whom the property resides, and the maxim, res perit domino, is applicable to sales.
